@@eThe Great Northern Forest -- As Kowloon Sees It@@N

@@yHarbor Syndics' Trade Assessment, Northern Corridor@@N

The forest is not wilderness to us. It is the @@gsouthern lifeline@@N --
the only overland artery connecting Kowloon to Midgaard's markets and,
through them, to the continent's inland economy. Every bolt of silk,
every cask of salt fish, every barrel of phosphorescent dye that leaves
our @@lTide Gate@@N by land must pass beneath those four hundred miles of
canopy. The @@yLantern Road@@N is not a curiosity. It is survival.

The Courier Lantern Office maintains that the @@yBent Mile Principle@@N --
Ilren Voss's doctrine of roads that yield to terrain -- is the oldest
expression of what we now call @@ecivic lantern-keeping@@N. Our own signal
network descends from the same tradition: light placed where it is
needed, not where it looks impressive. Every lantern post on the Road
bears knot-signs our @@eLampkeepers@@N can still read. That lineage is
not symbolic. It is @@yoperational@@N.

The @@WNorthern Covenant@@N -- the pact that forbids armies on the Road
and protects shrine groves -- was signed at the Oath-Crossing glade.
The Jade Magistracy notes with approval that its structure mirrors
our own @@yNeon Covenant@@N: an agreement inked in the open, resistant
to alteration in darkness. We trust compacts that glow under scrutiny.

The @@rAsh Winters@@N hit the forest two centuries ago, poisoning streams
and killing game. We remember this because the same volcanic fallout
from the @@dCinderteeth@@N became our @@rAshfall Monsoon@@N. The forest's
suffering and ours share a common source. The @@yPassage Tithe@@N system
that emerged -- payment in grain, salt, lamp oil, and iron nails --
is a language the Harbor Syndics understand instinctively. Coin fails
where material need speaks plainly.

Five zones ring the Road. The @@gSouthern Verge@@N is Midgaard's porch.
The @@lMosswater Bends@@N are treacherous crossings our caravans dread.
The @@dIronpine Rise@@N swallows lantern light. The @@eAncestor Deeps@@N
glow with luminescent moss -- the Courier Lantern Office calls this
the Forest's own Neon Covenant, light that cannot be forged. And the
@@WNorthern Crown@@N is ours. Our @@dWardens of Iron@@N conduct clearing
patrols there, keeping the road open within half a day's march of
the @@gJade Gate@@N.

The @@rAshfang warbands@@N trouble us. Exiles who blacken their teeth
with ash and sell intelligence to the highest bidder -- they mock
the @@dAshfall Vigil@@N by wearing catastrophe as decoration. The
Wardens mark them @@rcrimson@@N in the threat registry.

When the lanterns on the Road go dark, Kowloon's markets feel it
within the week. We do not romanticize the forest. We @@ycount@@N on it.
